@remark *********************************************************************

@node BackgroundNode "Background Info"

@{b}Background Info@{ub}
@{b}===============@{ub}

@{i}PopFile@{ui} is a small commodity intended for the WBStartup directory that
waits  for  you to press its hotkey. When you do, it opens an ASL file
requester and inserts the names of the files you select into the input
stream  of  the  active  window.  There is an option to have the names
expanded into fully qualified pathnames.

It  is  up to you to make sure that the application which receives the
filenames  (which  will appear as if typed in) does something suitable
with  them.  If  the  cursor  is in a string gadget, for example, that
would  usually  be fine. If the keypresses happen to cause the program
receiving  them to format your hard disk, though, that's your problem.
Admittedly  this  is pretty unlikely, especially as the input will not
include the return key.


@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node RequirementsNode "Requirements"

@{b}Requirements@{ub}
@{b}============@{ub}

@{i}PopFile@{ui} requires AmigaOS 2.04 / Kickstart V37 or higher.

The  following  disk-based  Commodore  libraries are required, but are
part of AmigaOS 2.04 anyway:

    o asl.library V37 or higher.
    o commodities.library V37 or higher.

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node InstallationNode "Installation"

@{b}Installation@{ub}
@{b}============@{ub}

Installation  is  trivial,  just drag @{i}PopFile@{ui} to any drawer you prefer
and drop it. If you put it in your WBStartUp drawer it will be started
every  time  you boot to the Workbench. Just check that "DONOTWAIT" is
present in the tooltypes. The other typical location is with the other
commodities in "SYS:Tools/Commodities".

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node StartingNode "Starting and Quiting"

@{b}Starting and Quitting@{ub}
@{b}=====================@{ub}

@{i}PopFile@{ui}  can  be  started  from  both Workbench and Shell. If run from
Workbench,  it  will configure itself by reading its icon's @{"tooltypes" link TooltypesNode}.
If  run  from  a  Shell,  you can specify some command line arguments.
These have the same format as the tooltypes.

@{i}PopFile@{ui} does not have a window as such but instead runs as a commodity
in  the  background.  To remove it, run it again, or select the "Kill"
option  of  the  Exchange  program.  You  can  also remove it with the
"Break" command using the "C" option.

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************


@node UsingNode "Using PopFile"

@{b}Using PopFile@{ub}
@{b}=============@{ub}

When  you press the hotkey, @{i}PopFile@{ui} will open an ASL file requester on
the active screen. Choose one or more files and select "Okay". @{i}PopFile@{ui}
will  insert those names into the program as though you had typed them
in  at the keyboard. Then it will go back to sleep until you summon it
again.

If  the @{"EXPANDNAMES" link TooltypesNode} option is turned on, PopFile will try to determine
the  full  pathname  of the selected file and input that. Otherwise it
will use the directory and filename present in the file requester.

If  you select multiple files, each name will be separated by a space.
If  any  pathname  has  embedded spaces, it will be enclosed in double
quotation  marks  (").  @{i}PopFile@{ui} will not send a Return keypress at the
end.

The  default  hotkey  is  "RCommand  RShift v" (right Amiga with right
Shift  and  "v").  You  can select your own hotkey using the @{b}CX_POPKEY@{ub}
@{"tooltype" link TooltypesNode}.

Remember   that  @{i}PopFile@{ui}  cannot  know  what  effect  these  simulated
keypresses  may  have on a program, so it's up to you to make sure the
context is suitable.

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node TooltypesNode "PopFile Tooltypes"

@{b}PopFile Tooltypes@{ub}
@{b}=================@{ub}

These  are  the  tooltypes  @{i}PopFile@{ui} looks for in its program icon (the
Shell argument keywords are the same):

@{b}EXPANDNAMES@{ub}

    Enables pathname expansion.
    Default: No expansion.


@{b}CX_POPKEY=<keydefstr>@{ub}

    Pop-up hotkey definition.
    Default: "RCommand RShift v"


@{b}CX_PRIORITY=<hotkeypri>@{ub}

    Hotkey priority among commodities.
    Default: 0


@{b}DONOTWAIT@{ub}

    This is actually read by Workbench when you put @{i}PopFile@{ui} in the
    WBStartup drawer. It tells Workbench not to wait for the program
    to finish before proceeding.

@endnode

